    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but the stakeholders are pretty persistent... like they don't really respect the \"review process\" and just keep pushing small things through. is there a more formal way to document this so they see how much it's actually hurting the timeline? maybe something like a change control board or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In that case, establishing a Change Control Board (CCB) or a formal review process can be a good way to keep stakeholders accountable. A CCB typically involves a cross-functional team that reviews and evaluates changes to the project scope, identifying potential risks and impacts on the timeline and budget. You can also use a tool like an Issue Management System, like Jira, to track and prioritize changes, and provide clear visibility into the project's scope and progress.",
      "source": "target",
